entry.title: Revert "[Extensions] Avoid starting a worker when it is already running."
entry.content:
This reverts commit 597f8713da69d0976fb52f41e3c32c0b38f855c9.



Reason for revert: Exposes a stack overflow bug: crbug.com/1490783. This keeps the feature defined though so we can re-enable it in the future



Original change's description:

> [Extensions] Avoid starting a worker when it is already running.

>

> This removes one case where we start a service worker in response to an

> event needing to be dispatched.

>

> Before this change we didn't check the running status of a worker and

> instead would start a worker if there were no pending tasks. A worker in

> blink::EmbeddedWorkerStatus::kRunning status is ready to receive events

> immediately though.

>

> This practically means that if multiple tasks built-up mometarily before

> ServiceWorkerTaskQueue::DidStartWorkerForScope() finished running we

> wouldn't try to start a worker. But all other times we would. For

> example: taskA is dispatched and causes the worker to start. TaskB

> comes into ServiceWorkerTaskQueue::AddPendingTask() a moment later after

> the worker has started (when the worker is most likely still running)

> and we redundantly attempt to start the worker.

>

> After this change if the worker has

> blink::EmbeddedWorkerStatus::kRunning status when TaskB arrives it will

> not cause us to redundantly attempt to start the worker when it is in

> this status.

>

> This new behavior is disabled by default and will be enabled with via a

> rollout due to it's potential wide impact on MV3/service workers.

>

entry.title: DOM: Observable subscription callback gets a `Subscriber` interface
entry.content:
This CL introduces the Observable API's `Subscriber` interface, which

includes the `next()`, `complete()`, and `error()` methods, in addition

to a possibly-null `AbortSignal`. All of these correspond 1:1 with the

members of the `Observable` dictionary (that gets passed into

`subscribe()`), that was introduced in https://crrev.com/c/4904693.



This CL passes a lot of previously-failing Observable WPTs, with some

corner-case error handling behavior left for future CLs. Specifically,

a subsequent CL will implement:

- Automatically invoking the Observer's `error()` handler when

exceptions are "thrown" in the subscribe callback (provided the

subscription is still open). Currently, the `error()` handler is only

invoked for manual invocations of `Subscriber#error()`.

- Reporting errors to the global [1] if an Observable tries to:

- Explicitly push an error to `Subscriber#error()`, when the given

Observer has no error handler

- Explicitly push an error to `Subscriber#error()` after the

subscription has already been closed



[1]: https://html.spec.whatwg.org/C#report-the-exception

entry.title: shortcuts: Prevent dialog update when accelerator update is in progress
entry.content:
Problem: When accelerator is modified, onAcceleratorsUpdated() will be

triggered, and dialog will be updated. This happens before

the AcceleratorConfigResult is returned from backend. After

that, result is returned and fireUpdate() will call

onRequestUpdateAccelerators(), which will update dialog

again. Ideally, we should only update dialog once for one

action.



Fix: Introduce acceleratorUpdateInProgress, and do not update dialog

in onAcceleratorsUpdated() when accelerator is update in

progress.



With this change:

- The onRequestUpdateAccelerators() will handle the dialog update

when there's an accelerator modification.

- The onAcceleratorsUpdated() manage dialog updates for other events,

such as input changes, keyboard plugged in, or pref change.

entry.title: Avoid CustomStyleForAltText during ResolveStyle
entry.content:
During HTMLImageElement::AdjustStyle, we do something very shady:

we poke into the UA shadow and mutate the inline style of some

of the elements in there. This causes style to be marked dirty

*during* style recalc, which is not a desirable situation.

The behavior would normally trigger a DCHECK, but it is currently

suppressed with by AllowMarkStyleDirtyFromRecalcScope.



Marking style dirty deeper in the current subtree works (sort of),

because we'll eventually reach those elements during the current

style recalc process anyway, so ultimately the dirtiness is

cleared. However, StyleResolver::ResolveStyle can also be called

*outside* of style recalc. For example, when producing styles

for kFirstLineInherited, we call ResolveStyle during *layout*.

In this case, there is no greater style recalc process ongoing,

so the dirtiness isn't cleared, and we trigger DCHECKs

(Issue 1486128).



This CL avoids the issue by reintroducing InputTypeView::

CustomStyleForLayoutObject, and making ImageInputType use that

mechanism instead of AdjustStyle. (Effectively a partial revert

of CL:4110875). This avoids the crash by relying on another bug:

when producing kFirstLineInherited styles, we ignore custom styles,

i.e. CustomStyleForLayoutObject never gets called (but AdjustStyle

does).

entry.title: Reuse the initial RFH in an unused SiteInstance for WebUI navigations.
entry.content:
WebUI navigations require a BrowsingInstance swap, and currently this

applies even to navigations to WebUI URLs out of an initial blank

RenderFrameHost in a new WebContents, which causes a swap to a new

RenderFrameHost. This is unnecessary, since the initial

RenderFrameHost has an unassigned SiteInstance (HasSite() is false)

and an unused/unlocked process, so it actually satisfies WebUI's

"fresh" BrowsingInstance requirement.



This CL makes it possible to reuse the initial RenderFrameHost for

WebUI navigations. ShouldSwapBrowsingInstancesForNavigation() is

changed to not require a BrowsingInstance swap in this case. New

logic is added to lock the initial RenderFrameHost's process and

assign a site to its SiteInstance as soon as it's reused for WebUI,

matching the behavior when a speculative RFH is created. (Normally,

unassigned SiteInstances assign a site at OnResponseStarted time, but

with WebUI we can't, and shouldn't, wait that long, as a locked

process is needed to pass WebUI security checks in places like

AllowBindings() that happen before OnResponseStarted.)



WebUI is likely the largest use case where the initial RFH can't

currently be reused by a new navigation (the others being

guests and Android's dynamic isolation). This CL removes that case

and aligns initial WebUI navigation behavior with normal navigations.



This change will simplify moving the early RFH swap to be done later,

since we won't need to worry about assumptions made by some code about

having WebUI objects available after kicking off a navigation of a

WebUI URL in a new blank WebContents. Currently, the early swap

guarantees that the speculative RFH will be committed immediately, but

moving the swap to happen later would've broken some of these implicit

assumptions.



This change also required relaxing IsSuitableHost() to allow an unused

process with no WebUI bindings to be used for a WebUI navigation.

This proved to be subtle: allowing any unused RPH to be freely reused

for WebUI processes broke some chrome://*.top-chrome/ WebUI tests,

where navigations to a top-chrome WebUI URL rely on always reusing an

existing top-chrome WebUI process when one is available, and which

break if an unused process from an unrelated tab is reused instead.

Therefore, a heuristic was added to only allow an unused initial

process to be reused for a navigation in that same BrowsingInstance.

Intuitively, this means that an unused process from an initial RFH is

intended to be reused by a navigation in that same frame, but not by

navigations in unrelated windows, since the latter would likely lead

to a process swap when the frame actually navigates.

entry.title: Check if profile exists before starting DownloadActivity
entry.content:
DownloadActivity#onCreate calls OTRProfileID#deserialize to get the

OTRProfileID from intent. In some cases this causes a crashes due to

the OTR profile not being available for a given OTRProfileID. This was

previously fixed by adding a check in

DownloadUtils#showDownloadManager() before starting DownloadActivity.

However, the DownloadActivity#onCreate can still be called without

going through the check in DownloadUtils#showDownloadManager(), for

example: when the activity is killed in the background and needs to be

restarted.

This change adds an additional check to DownloadActivity before calling

OTRProfileID#deserialize.

Apps could be installed as standalone apps as well as sub apps.

entry.title: [Autofill] Reorganise ContentAutofillDriver, AutofillDriverRouter
entry.content:
The members of ContentAutofillDriver and AutofillDriverRouter fall

into a few groups, the two largest of which consist of events that

are routed between drivers, with one group consisting of

browser->renderer events and the other vice versa.



Maintaining this has proved difficult: some newly added functions

ended up in the wrong group, leading to incorrect comments.



This CL updates the organisation of the files and updates several

comments. It splits the two main groups into subgroups depending

on how they are routed:

- broadcast to all drivers or managers;

- routed to a specific agent or manager;

- passed on to the driver's agent.



This CL also extends comments in autofill_driver_router.cc to

explain why some events are broadcast.



Finally, this CL renames TriggerFormExtraction() to

TriggerFormExtractionInDriverFrame() to make the contrast to

TriggerFormExtractionInAllFrames() more explicit.

entry.title: LoAF: change the way script nesting is handled
entry.content:
The logic to avoid nested scripts (only count for entry points)

was not handling the fact that script blocks can be nested in

callbacks and vice-versa.



The stack is a lot clearer now, with all script probes calling

PushScriptEntryPoint & PopScriptEntryPoint, the exception being

promise-resolver, which pops only when the task is complete.



The probe handling for script blocks is now changed, so that

ExecuteScript either creates a module entry or sets the execution time

on a script that has started.



Moved script internal timings (layout/style/alert/sync-XHR) to the end of the file (unmodified).



Added a few tests that reproduce the nesting issue, and removed the test

that relies on trusted-types as we don't require that dependency.



Also this fix changes a few existing test results:

- A script block executed synchronously from within a callback is

attributed to the callback, as it's nested. The way to reproduce

a top level classic script block is to have it parsed from the

HTML.



- There is no more "execute-script" type, that's now a module.
